  "doc_id": "30807",
  "text": "In documenting a differential infection rate with MIS versus conventional surgery, Andreshak et al. [CITATION_1] reported a 13% infection rate for obese patients (defined as Ͼ20% over ideal body weight) with traditional open spinal procedures. Rodgers and Michitsch 12 analyzed a subset of obese patients. They reported a 4.2% infection rate in 144 obese patients undergoing instrumented open posterior lumbar fusions. Rodgers et al. [CITATION_2] performed a retrospective review of 313 patients operated on from October 2006 to July 2008 undergoing MIS far lateral interbody fusions-156 were obese (defined as body mass index Ͼ30) and 157 were nonobese. There were no SSIs in this group. Within the same institution, with the same surgeons, this was an improvement from a 4.2% infection rate in 144 open procedures to 0% in 156 MIS procedures in obese patients.",
